snippet.textDisplay:
Culture is an amalgam of values, meanings and conventions. With Kobe Bryant’s tragic accident
Coupled with the loss of his daughter and the recent pictures of him interacting with her, the cultural grieving is still very strong.
It’s human nature to collectively process this loss with empathy.
The way we do this is through “parasocial bonding”, “counter factual thinking” (if only they had not
gotten on the helicopter, if only. And then “fear control”. When that grieving is still going on it's not good
to disrupt that process and shake people out of this process into reality. Journalists should be coached
to not disrupt this until much later. All I can say is that Kobe did not let his mistakes define him.
Is there ever redemption ? For Gayle King it would have been wise to understand this very public grieving, despite the thirst for “Balanced Reporting”.
